title: Ex-WWE star, Texas native Chavo Classic has died

Photo: WWE Image 1 of / 96 96 A one-time WWE superstar has died One-time WWE superstar and El Paso, Texas native Chavo Guerrero Sr., has died. He was 68. Salvador "Chavo Classic" Guerro III has died at age 68.
His son announced the death on Instagram on Feb. 11, 2017. Chavo Jr., said his father was diagnosed with liver cancer in January.
Photo: Instagram A true rebel Chavo Guerrero Sr., known as Chavo Classic to wrestling fans, died Feb. 11, 2017. His son, Chavo Guerrero Jr., made the announcement on Instagram, saying "Today, the world lost a true rebel." A true rebel Chavo Guerrero Sr., known as Chavo Classic to wrestling... He did things "HIS" way. Not always right, not always wrong, but He always followed what he believed in," Chavo Jr. said. "As believer in Christ Jesus, he is now in Paradise."

On his Facebook page , fans grieved his loss and thanked him for years of entertainment.
"Rest in peace compadre...thank you for always being a good friend to your fans," Mario Salas wrote.
Chavo Classic, a native of El Paso, Texas, first hit the wrestling scene in the NWA Hollywood Wrestling territory. There, he was 15-time champion and a longtime rival of WWE Hall of Famer "Rowdy" Roddy Piper.

Chavo Classic made the jump to the WWE Universe in 2004 and did it in a big way. He plunged into an ongoing rivalry between his brother Eddie and son, Chavo Jr., himself a WWE superstar.
That year, Chavo Classic became the oldest WWE superstar to win the original Cruiserweight Championship.
In noting his father's passing, Chavo Jr. used the hastag #nowinheaven and noted: "Today the world lost a true rebel."
